{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512339"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:53:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.16,0.32,0.08,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115151"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97159"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1044"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15218"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48767"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115151"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 21-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for his annual review. He was diagnosed with coeliac disease two years ago based on a small intestine biopsy and positive serologic results for serum anti-endomysial immunoglobulin A (IgA) antibodies. He has no significant medical history apart from coeliac disease and takes no regular medications. His doctor advised him to follow a gluten-free diet. At this review, the patient reports that he tries to adhere to the diet but is not always certain if he selects gluten-free items. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to assess diet adherence and treatment efficacy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform a repeat small intestinal biopsy","Measure serum anti-endomysial IgA antibodies","Measure serum anti-tissue transglutaminase IgA antibodies","Measure faecal fat","Measure serum anti-gliadin IgG antibodies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a repeat small intestinal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step to assess diet adherence and treatment efficacy in this patient with coeliac disease. Small intestinal biopsy remains the gold standard for evaluating mucosal healing and confirming strict adherence to a gluten-free diet. Complete recovery from villous atrophy provides definitive evidence that the gluten-free diet has been followed effectively, regardless of serological antibody titres or symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasuring serum anti-endomysial IgA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is less reliable than a biopsy for assessing diet adherence. While these antibodies are highly specific for coeliac disease, their levels may not accurately reflect small dietary indiscretions or variations. Serological tests can be useful for initial diagnosis and monitoring, but they cannot provide the same level of certainty as histological examination of the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum anti-tissue transglutaminase IgA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is another serological test used in coeliac disease monitoring. However, like anti-endomysial antibodies, it may not detect minor dietary transgressions and is less reliable than a biopsy for assessing mucosal healing and diet adherence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasuring faecal fat\u003C/strong\u003E is not a specific test for coeliac disease or for assessing adherence to a gluten-free diet. While malabsorption can lead to increased faecal fat, this finding is neither sensitive nor specific for coeliac disease activity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasuring serum anti-gliadin IgG antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is less specific and sensitive than other serological tests for coeliac disease. These antibodies are no longer recommended for routine diagnosis or monitoring of coeliac disease due to their poor performance compared to anti-endomysial and anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that adult patients with coeliac disease often present with atypical or asymptomatic forms of the disease, making clinical-based monitoring less valuable. A repeat biopsy can also detect refractory coeliac disease, which occurs in less than 2% of patients and is characterised by persistent small intestinal damage despite strict adherence to a gluten-free diet. If the repeat biopsy shows normal mucosa and serology has normalized, it suggests good compliance with the gluten-free diet. In such cases, annual serological checks and biennial bone mineral density studies are typically recommended for ongoing monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small intestinal biopsy is the gold standard for assessing mucosal healing and adherence to a gluten-free diet in coeliac disease.","Serological tests may not detect small dietary indiscretions in coeliac disease.","Refractory coeliac disease, characterized by persistent small intestinal damage despite adherence to a gluten-free diet, occurs in less than 2% of patients."],"references":["Rodrigo L, P\u00e9rez-Martinez I, Lauret-Bra\u00f1a E, Su\u00e1rez-Gonz\u00e1lez A. Descriptive Study of the Different Tools Used to Evaluate the Adherence to a Gluten-Free Diet in Celiac Disease Patients. Nutrients. 2018 Nov 16;10(11):1777. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6267102/","Tye-Din JA. Interpreting tests for coeliac disease: Tips, pitfalls and updates. Aust J Gen Pract. 2018; 47:28-33. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2018/january-february/interpreting-tests-for-coeliac-disease-1","Rubio-Tapia A, Hill ID, Semrad C, et al. American College of Gastroenterology Guidelines  Update: Diagnosis and Management of Celiac Disease. Am J Gastroenterol 2023;118:59\u201376."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97159"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97159"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T16:24:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T16:25:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4479"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115151"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attribu